    summary:
      "Andorra should currently be mapped as a compact, distributed system rather than as a country with a single national research-misconduct board. AQUA is the central higher-education quality-assurance actor and its mandate reaches institutional and research-quality evaluation, but its public outputs are QA evaluations, appeals routes, annual reports and academic-integrity research, not a general misconduct case archive. The University of Andorra is the strongest institutional research-governance route through its Research and Doctoral Commission, doctoral programme milestones, research-group regulation and plagiarism/fraud procedure; these sources expose procedure and quality-control pathways rather than public misconduct decisions. Government research funding is visible through third-cycle and research-support calls, while Andorra Recerca + Innovacio is a public-sector research and innovation foundation rather than an adjudicator. Biomedical research is a separate boundary lane under Law 3/2023 and the Ministry of Health Comissio d'Etica de la Investigacio. Public case visibility remains low: the clearest public decision material is AQUA QA reporting and APDA data-protection resolutions, both of which must be kept separate from general research-integrity findings.",
