      "Armenia should currently be mapped as a degree-award and institution-led research-governance system rather than as a country with a single national research-misconduct board. The Higher Education and Science Committee's degree platform preserves the Supreme Certifying Committee route: specialized academic councils handle dissertation defenses, the committee approves and certifies scientific degrees and titles, can refuse awards where regulatory violations occur, and publishes degree/title orders and defense metadata. HESC grant calls add funder-side integrity controls through publication-quality checks, reporting duties, termination rules and future-application consequences, but no public grant-misconduct archive was located. ANQA publishes higher-education accreditation decisions, expert reports and a state accreditation register, which are important quality-assurance files but not general misconduct decisions. The most concrete ethics-handling evidence remains institutional and boundary-specific: NIH, YSMU, AUA and the Institute of Molecular Biology expose research ethics or IRB routes, while clinical trials, animal experiments, data protection and IP sit in separate legal or regulatory lanes. Public case visibility remains low for general research misconduct.",
    keyActors: [
      "Higher Education and Science Committee / Supreme Certifying Committee degree route",
      "Specialized academic councils",
      "HESC state research-grant programmes",
      "National Center for Professional Education Quality Assurance Foundation (ANQA)",
      "National Institute of Health Ethics Committee",
      "Yerevan State Medical University Ethics Committee",
      "American University of Armenia Institutional Review Boards",
      "Institute of Molecular Biology Ethics Committee",
      "Medicines authority and Clinical Trials Ethics Commission",
      "Personal Data Protection Agency and Intellectual Property Office as boundary actors"
    ],
