    summary:
      "Azerbaijan should currently be mapped through the Higher Attestation Commission under the President of the Republic of Azerbaijan (AAK), not as a country with one general research-misconduct board. AAK controls scientific degrees, academic titles, dissertation councils, expert councils, appeals and attestation documents, and it publishes dissertation-defense metadata, dissertation and abstract records, degree-recognition records, regulations and news. The strongest public case signal found in this pass is AAK's 30 September 2025 notice describing an 8 May 2024 plagiarism-based deprivation of a PhD degree and associate-professor title, followed by a 19 September 2025 AAK Presidium decision annulling that deprivation after a 10 July 2025 Supreme Court decision. AAK also publishes interviews and statistics on plagiarism-based refusals and scientific-ethics controls, but no comprehensive searchable misconduct-decision archive was identified. Around that national attestation corridor, TKTA publishes higher-education accreditation reports and annual reports, the Azerbaijan Science Foundation provides grant infrastructure, universities publish ethics, plagiarism or research-ethics rules, and clinical, data, IP, animal and open-science matters sit in separate boundary lanes.",
