    summary:
      "Georgia should currently be mapped as a distributed research-governance system. The Law on Science, Technology and Their Development, the Law on Higher Education and the Law on the Georgian National Academy of Sciences create the national science, higher-education and annual scientific-assessment frame, but they do not expose a single national research-misconduct board. The clearest current national reform signal is the EU-funded ETHICS project, coordinated by Ilia State University with the Ministry, NCEQE and SRNSFG as partners, which is explicitly building research-integrity policy, modules, integrity officers, university research-integrity policies and research-integrity ethics boards. NCEQE publishes quality-assurance decisions, reports and the HEI register; these are important public accountability files but remain QA rather than general misconduct decisions. SRNSFG provides funder-side competition and monitoring infrastructure. Practical ethics and integrity handling is visible mainly at institutions: TSU's academic-integrity policy and ETHICS participation, TSMU's Biomedical Research Ethics Committee, Ilia's faculty REC, East European University's REC and Caucasus International University's 2025 Scientific Research Ethics Council. Public general misconduct case publication was not located in this first pass.",
