    summary:
      "Luxembourg has a small but unusually coherent research-integrity system. The Luxembourg Agency for Research Integrity (LARI), founded in 2016 by the public research actors, is the national research integrity office and the central prevention, advice and investigation hub. Its Commission for Research Integrity (CRI) handles alleged research misconduct for LARI member organisations and FNR-funded research through an independent international committee. Final reports remain confidential, so public transparency is mainly through statutes, procedures, data-sharing agreements, the FNR MoU, annual reporting and rare funder communications rather than a public case archive. The current LARI page still marks the 2023/2024 annual report as coming soon, while the 2020-2022 report gives aggregate case counts and the 2020 FNR statement is the clearest case-level public fragment. Around LARI sit FNR funding obligations, the University of Luxembourg's research integrity, ethics review, animal ethics and whistleblowing routes, institute-level ethics and quality structures at LIST, LIH and LISER, and the separate CNER/CNPD/animal-use boundary systems.",
