    summary:
      "Liechtenstein should be read as a small, institution-led system rather than as a LOWI-style national appeal model. The Office of Education identifies two state-recognized universities with degree-awarding powers, the University of Liechtenstein and the Private University in the Principality of Liechtenstein (UFL), and one university-like research institute, the Liechtenstein Institute. The Higher Education Act and University of Liechtenstein Act give the statutory frame, while practical research-integrity handling is visible at institution level: the University of Liechtenstein publishes a Good Scientific Practice route with Research Support Office advice and an independent ombudsperson, and UFL publishes research-integrity guidance, an ombudsperson route, a Disciplinary Board link and rules for safeguarding good scientific practice. No national general research-misconduct decision archive or public institutional misconduct case archive was located in this first pass. Publicly visible adjacent systems are stronger for higher-education quality, research funding access, clinical-trial and medical-device authorisation, data protection, IP, and animal experiments.",
