      "Statutory national-council and institutional-procedure model with an independent council that issues opinions and recommendations without direct sanctions, above varied university and institute routes and a strong open-science layer.",
    summary:
      "Slovenia should now be coded as a statutory council-and-institution model rather than a centralized misconduct tribunal. Article 39 of the Scientific Research and Innovation Activity Act (ZZrID) obliges research organizations and researchers to uphold scientific integrity and good scientific practice, requires organizational measures against breaches, and establishes the National Council for Ethics and Integrity in Science. The council uses the European Code of Conduct for Research Integrity, issues opinions, recommendations and annual reports, and coordinates nationally, but its 2023-2025 work report states that it cannot impose sanctions and that research organizations are not clearly bound to act on its opinions. The committee-and-case-file pass shows that Slovenia explicitly merges the language of ethics and integrity at the national-council level: the procedure covers both compliance with ethical rules and breaches of research-integrity principles, requires anonymized publication of issued opinions, and reports one ARIS-referred initiative that did not become a proceeding because the conduct was not treated as a breach. Practical handling remains distributed across universities and institutes such as Ljubljana, Maribor, Primorska and ZRC SAZU, while Article 40, the open-science decree, ARIS implementation, medical ethics, animal-experiment rules, data protection and public-integrity controls shape the surrounding system.",
