    summary:
      "Croatia should now be mapped as a post-2022 decentralized institutional system rather than as a national misconduct-board model. The Law on Higher Education and Scientific Activity obliges every higher education institution and scientific institute to establish an ethics committee, adopt an ethics code, and maintain disciplinary rules and a disciplinary committee. The National Council for Higher Education, Science and Technological Development supplies the national standard-setting layer and is tasked with adopting minimum ethical principles, but the operative routes remain local. The case-file sweep confirms a split publication picture: the old parliamentary Odbor za etiku left public reports and individual named opinions, but the current system has no equivalent national case archive; Zagreb exposes annual-report statistics and appeal traces, Rijeka exposes principled opinions and statements, HRZZ exposes a funder integrity procedure without public opinions, and Split exposes planned anonymized reporting rather than located case outputs. Around that core sit the 2022 quality-assurance law and AZVO reaccreditation cycle, ministry registers and CroRIS, university and institute routes at Zagreb, Rijeka, Split and the Rudjer Boskovic Institute, and separate biomedical, clinical-trial, animal, data-protection, intellectual-property and open-science regimes.",
