      "Federal constitutional and funder-anchored self-regulatory model with the DFG code as the practical national minimum, OWID as the confidential national ombuds layer, DFG's own inquiry and sanction route, and wide institutional and specialist implementation across universities, research organizations and boundary regimes.",
    summary:
      "Germany should not be coded as a single national misconduct-board system. The strongest national baseline is Article 5(3) of the Basic Law together with the DFG's 2019 Code of Conduct and the rule that institutions must implement its 19 guidelines in legally binding form if they want DFG funding. That national minimum is then operationalized through a distributed network: OWID offers confidential nationwide advice and mediation but does not act as a sanctioning appeals court; DFG investigates and sanctions DFG-related misconduct under its own 2024 Rules of Procedure; universities and university medical centers run local ombudsperson and committee routes; and Helmholtz, Leibniz, Max Planck and Fraunhofer each maintain their own organization-wide structures. Clinical trials, medical-device studies, animal research, data protection, research-data stewardship, security-relevant research and export control remain visible adjacent regimes rather than one merged integrity chain.",
